# S&P Index Lab — AI Assistant Rules

## Project Context
AI-powered portfolio analytics platform proving the S&P 500 is a ~20-stock index. Python backend computes analytics (OLS regression, variance decomposition, mirror indices). React frontend displays results via an interactive machine-metaphor visualization with SVG animations. Static JSON bridge between the two — no Python at runtime.

## Python Code Style
- Python 3.11+ with type hints on all function signatures
- Google-style docstrings on all public functions
- Use `logging` module, never `print()` in library code
- Vectorized pandas/numpy operations, never `iterrows()`
- Financial values: round to 4 decimal places
- Imports: stdlib → third-party → local, separated by blank lines
- Constants from `src/config.py` — never hardcode tickers or thresholds

## TypeScript/React Code Style
- Strict TypeScript — all props and data typed in `lib/types.ts`
- Components: `components/{feature}/{ComponentName}.tsx`
- Hooks: `hooks/use{Name}.ts`
- Design tokens in `lib/constants.ts` — no inline colors or timing values
- Tailwind CSS v4 with `@theme inline` syntax, custom dark tokens
- Framer Motion for animations — use spring physics, not duration-based
- Snake_case JSON keys → camelCase TypeScript via transform layer

## Architecture Rules
- All data fetching through `src/data/fetcher.py` — no direct yfinance elsewhere
- All DB operations through `src/data/storage.py` — no direct Supabase elsewhere
- Frontend reads static JSON from `/public/data/` — never calls Python
- No look-ahead bias in any calculation — only past data at decision time
- ML models must be serializable (joblib) and versioned
- Dashboard pre-computes everything — never calculate on render

## Key Libraries
### Python
- pandas, numpy, statsmodels: Data / analytics
- scikit-learn: OLS LinearRegression for R² analysis
- yfinance: Market data source
- PyPortfolioOpt: Portfolio optimization (HRP, Black-Litterman, MVO)
- LightGBM: Factor model scoring
- hmmlearn: Regime detection (GaussianHMM)

### TypeScript
- Next.js 16 (App Router), React 19
- Framer Motion 12+: Animations
- Recharts 3: Charts (line, area, bar)
- @radix-ui/react-tooltip: Accessible tooltips
- Tailwind CSS v4: Styling
- clsx + tailwind-merge: Class utilities

## Testing
- pytest with fixtures for sample data
- Financial calculations: test with known analytical solutions
- ML models: test input/output shapes, constraint satisfaction
- Never test with live API calls — use fixtures/mocks
- Frontend: `npm run build` as type-check gate

## Common Patterns

### Data transform (useLabData.ts)
```typescript
function transformPerformanceNav(raw: any): PerformanceNavData {
  const source = raw.weekly || raw.recent_daily || [];
  return source.map((p: any): PerformanceNavPoint => ({
    date: p.date ?? "",
    sp500: p.sp500 ?? 0,
    sp20Mirror: p.sp20_mirror ?? p.sp20Mirror ?? 0,
    sp20Equal: p.sp20_equal ?? p.sp20Equal ?? 0,
  }));
}
```

### Machine state (useMachineState.ts)
```typescript
// useReducer-based state machine: IDLE → stages → COMPLETE
type MachineStage = "idle" | "powering_up" | "data_pipeline" | "concentration"
  | "building" | "optimizing" | "monitoring" | "complete";
```

### Portfolio weight constraints
```python
def apply_constraints(weights: dict[str, float]) -> dict[str, float]:
    clipped = {k: np.clip(v, MIN_POSITION_WEIGHT, MAX_POSITION_WEIGHT)
               for k, v in weights.items()}
    total = sum(clipped.values())
    return {k: v / total for k, v in clipped.items()}
```

## Constraints
- Free tier: Supabase 500MB, GitHub Actions 2000 min/month
- Transaction costs: 5 bps round-trip for backtesting
- Frontend purely static — no server-side Python
- Time series downsampled to weekly for chart performance
